This capture utility should be kept as simple and straight forward as possible, and focus purely on easily doing Wi-Fi packet captures.

There is some room for minimal extra features.

There will be options to capture only specific types of traffic, like management, control, or data frames (or any combination of them).

There can be some specific sub-types too, like beacons, association, probe, EAPOL. This can be very useful when trying to capture clients joining a network, without having to capture everything else in the air and creating excessively large capture files.


--- PLANNED FEATURES ---


1. CHANNEL ANALYSIS PAGE (from live scan data)

Uses the existing /scan endpoint data to provide a complete RF environment overview.

Channel congestion map:
- Count how many APs are on each channel across 2.4 GHz, 5 GHz, and 6 GHz
- Display as horizontal bar chart showing AP count per channel
- Colour code: green (1-3 APs), yellow (4-6), red (7+)

Adjacent channel interference detection (2.4 GHz):
- Flag any AP operating on a non-standard channel (not 1, 6, or 11)
- These cause overlapping interference with neighbouring channels
- Display which channels are affected by each offending AP
- Example: AP on channel 3 interferes with both channel 1 and channel 6 networks

40 MHz channels in 2.4 GHz detection:
- Flag APs using HT40 (40 MHz wide channels) in the 2.4 GHz band
- In a congested environment this causes severe interference
- Only 1 non-overlapping 40 MHz channel exists in 2.4 GHz
- Detection: check HT Operation IE for secondary channel offset

Channel utilisation:
- Extract from BSS Load element in beacons (already parsed)
- station_count: how many clients the AP reports
- channel_utilisation: 0-255 value representing percentage of time the channel is busy
- Display as percentage per AP and averaged per channel
- Flag channels with utilisation > 60%

Optimal channel recommendation:
- Based on AP count, signal strengths, and utilisation per channel
- Suggest the least congested channel for each band
- For 2.4 GHz: recommend from 1, 6, 11 only
- For 5 GHz: consider DFS channels as options if supported


2. RETRY AND RETRANSMISSION ANALYSIS (from pcap)

The retry rate is one of the single most diagnostic metrics in Wi-Fi troubleshooting. A high retry rate indicates interference, distance problems, hidden nodes, or rate mismatch.

Extract retry flag:
- tshark field: wlan.fc.retry
- Every retransmitted frame has this bit set in the frame control field

Per-client retry rate:
- For each wireless client MAC address, count total frames and retry frames
- Calculate: retry_rate = (retry_frames / total_frames) * 100
- Flag clients with retry rate above 10% as problematic
- Flag above 20% as critical

Per-AP retry rate:
- Same calculation grouped by BSSID
- High AP retry rate suggests environmental issues affecting all clients on that AP

Retry rate breakdown by frame type:
- Separate retry rates for management, control, and data frames
- High management frame retries: possible interference
- High data frame retries: client distance or rate mismatch

Per-client retry details:
- Show which AP the client was associated with when retries occurred
- Correlate with signal strength (RSSI from radiotap header)
- Weak signal + high retries = distance or obstruction problem
- Strong signal + high retries = interference or hidden node

tshark extraction command:
  tshark -r file.pcap -Y "wlan.fc.type == 2" -T fields -E separator=\t \
    -e wlan.sa -e wlan.bssid -e wlan.fc.retry -e radiotap.dbm_antsignal

Problem detection rules:
- Client retry rate > 10%: "High retry rate on client {MAC} ({rate}%). Check distance or interference."
- Client retry rate > 20%: "Critical retry rate on client {MAC} ({rate}%). Likely significant interference or very weak signal."
- AP retry rate > 15%: "High retry rate on AP {BSSID} ({rate}%). Environmental issue affecting this AP's coverage area."


3. ROAMING ANALYSIS (from pcap)

Building on the existing client-to-AP association tracking to provide roaming quality metrics.

Roaming timeline:
- For each client that associated with multiple APs, build a timeline
- Show: timestamp, AP name/BSSID, duration on each AP
- Visualise as a horizontal bar chart or timeline

Roaming duration measurement:
- Gap between last frame on old AP and first frame on new AP
- Under 50ms: excellent (fast transition / 802.11r)
- 50-150ms: acceptable
- 150-500ms: noticeable to voice/video
- Over 500ms: problematic, will drop calls
- Flag slow roams as problems

Sticky client detection:
- Client stays on a distant AP despite being closer to another
- Detection: client signal strength (RSSI) below -75 dBm on current AP
  while the same client is later seen on a closer AP with better signal
- Flag as: "Client {MAC} stayed on {AP} at {RSSI} dBm for {duration} before roaming"

Excessive roaming (ping-pong):
- Client roams between the same two APs more than 3 times in 5 minutes
- Indicates: APs at similar signal levels, client is on the boundary
- Flag as: "Client {MAC} roaming excessively between {AP1} and {AP2}"

802.11r (Fast Transition) detection:
- Check if roaming used FT (802.11r) or full re-authentication
- FT roam: auth frame with algorithm 2 (Fast BSS Transition)
- Full roam: standard auth + association + EAPOL 4-way handshake
- Report: "X of Y roams used Fast Transition (802.11r)"

tshark fields for roaming:
  wlan.sa, wlan.bssid, frame.time_epoch, radiotap.dbm_antsignal,
  wlan.fc.type_subtype (filter for assoc req: 0x0000, reassoc req: 0x0002)


4. CLIENT CAPABILITY REPORT (from pcap)

Identify client device capabilities from their probe requests and association frames to find mismatches and legacy devices.

Client Wi-Fi generation:
- Parse HT Capabilities (802.11n), VHT Capabilities (802.11ac), HE Capabilities (802.11ax)
  from probe requests and association request frames
- Categorise each client: 11a/b/g, Wi-Fi 4 (n), Wi-Fi 5 (ac), Wi-Fi 6 (ax)
- Report distribution: "45% Wi-Fi 6, 30% Wi-Fi 5, 20% Wi-Fi 4, 5% legacy"

Supported bands:
- From probe requests: which frequencies/channels the client probes for
- Identify 2.4 GHz only clients (cannot use 5 GHz)
- These are either legacy devices or IoT devices

Legacy client identification:
- Flag clients that only support 802.11b/g
- These force the AP to use compatibility mechanisms that slow everyone down
- Flag as: "Legacy 802.11b/g client {MAC} ({vendor}) detected. This client reduces performance for all other clients on the same AP."

Capability mismatch detection:
- Compare client capabilities with AP capabilities
- Example: AP supports Wi-Fi 6 but client is Wi-Fi 4 — not a problem per se,
  but if all clients are Wi-Fi 5+, legacy compatibility could be disabled
- Report: "All detected clients support 802.11ac or newer. Consider disabling 802.11n compatibility."

Spatial streams:
- From HT/VHT/HE capabilities, determine supported spatial streams (1x1, 2x2, 3x3)
- Helps identify low-end devices that may underperform

tshark extraction:
  tshark -r file.pcap -Y "wlan.fc.type_subtype == 0x0004 || wlan.fc.type_subtype == 0x0000" \
    -T fields -E separator=\t \
    -e wlan.sa -e wlan.ht.capabilities -e wlan.vht.capabilities \
    -e wlan.ext.tag.number -e wlan.supported_rates


5. SIGNAL STRENGTH ANALYSIS (from pcap)

Radiotap headers contain RSSI (received signal strength) for every captured frame. This data is invaluable for coverage analysis.

Signal per client:
- For each client, extract RSSI from radiotap.dbm_antsignal
- Calculate: min, max, average, standard deviation
- High standard deviation suggests the client is moving or signal is unstable

Signal distribution:
- Histogram of signal strengths across all captured frames
- Buckets: excellent (> -50), good (-50 to -65), fair (-65 to -75), weak (-75 to -85), very weak (< -85)
- Shows overall coverage quality

Weak client detection:
- Clients with average RSSI below -75 dBm
- These clients experience: lower data rates, more retries, more packet loss
- Flag as: "Client {MAC} has weak signal (avg {RSSI} dBm). Check AP placement or client location."

Signal vs retry correlation:
- Cross-reference signal strength with retry rate per client
- Expected: weak signal correlates with high retries
- Unexpected: strong signal with high retries suggests interference (not distance)

Coverage gap indicators:
- If many clients on the same AP have weak signals, the AP may be poorly placed
- Flag as: "{N} clients on AP {name} have signal below -75 dBm. Consider AP placement."

tshark extraction:
  tshark -r file.pcap -Y "wlan.fc.type == 2" -T fields -E separator=\t \
    -e wlan.sa -e wlan.bssid -e radiotap.dbm_antsignal -e wlan.fc.retry


6. AIRTIME ANALYSIS (from pcap)

Airtime is the most important performance metric in Wi-Fi. A single slow client can consume more airtime than dozens of fast clients.

Data rate distribution:
- Extract radiotap.datarate or MCS index from each frame
- Group by: legacy rates (1-54 Mbps), HT rates (MCS 0-31), VHT rates, HE rates
- Show as histogram or pie chart
- Flag if more than 20% of frames use rates below 24 Mbps

Airtime estimation per client:
- Airtime is approximately proportional to: frame_size / data_rate
- For each client: sum(frame_size / data_rate) across all their frames
- Normalise to percentage of total airtime
- Identify "airtime hogs": clients consuming disproportionate airtime

Management frame overhead:
- Calculate percentage of all captured frames that are management frames
- Beacons are the biggest contributor
- With many SSIDs per AP, beacon overhead can exceed 20% of airtime
- Flag if beacon overhead > 10% of total frames

Probe request storm detection:
- Count probe requests per client
- Some clients (especially legacy) send excessive probe requests
- Flag if a single client sends > 100 probe requests per minute

Low data rate analysis:
- Identify frames transmitted at rates below 24 Mbps
- Group by client and AP
- Clients using low rates:
  - May be far away (check RSSI)
  - May be legacy devices (check capabilities)
  - May be experiencing interference (check retries)

tshark extraction:
  tshark -r file.pcap -T fields -E separator=\t \
    -e wlan.sa -e wlan.bssid -e radiotap.datarate -e frame.len \
    -e wlan.fc.type -e wlan.fc.type_subtype


7. DHCP AND DNS ANALYSIS (from pcap)

Network layer issues often manifest as Wi-Fi problems. Slow DHCP or DNS makes users think the Wi-Fi is broken.

DHCP timing:
- Extract DHCP Discover, Offer, Request, ACK timestamps
- Calculate: time from Discover to ACK (DHCP transaction time)
- Normal: under 1 second
- Slow: 1-5 seconds
- Problematic: over 5 seconds or timeouts (Discover with no Offer)
- Flag: "DHCP transaction for client {MAC} took {time}s. Check DHCP server."

DHCP failures:
- Discover without Offer: DHCP server unreachable
- Multiple Discovers: client retrying, server not responding
- DHCP NAK: address conflict or configuration issue

DNS timing:
- Extract DNS query and response pairs
- Calculate response time
- Normal: under 50ms
- Slow: 50-200ms
- Problematic: over 200ms or timeouts
- Flag slow DNS servers

tshark extraction for DHCP:
  tshark -r file.pcap -Y "dhcp" -T fields -E separator=\t \
    -e frame.time_epoch -e eth.src -e dhcp.type -e dhcp.ip.your

tshark extraction for DNS:
  tshark -r file.pcap -Y "dns" -T fields -E separator=\t \
    -e frame.time_epoch -e dns.id -e dns.flags.response -e dns.qry.name


8. REPORTING AND EXPORT

Generate a downloadable report summarising all findings.

Report format:
- HTML file that can be opened in any browser
- Self-contained (inline CSS, no external dependencies)
- Printable (print-friendly styles)

Report sections:
- Executive summary: total APs, clients, problems found, overall health score
- Network inventory: all SSIDs, APs, channels, security
- Problem list: all detected issues sorted by severity
- Client inventory: all detected clients with capabilities
- Recommendations: prioritised list of actions to improve the network

Health score:
- Calculate an overall score (0-100) based on:
  - Security (WPA3 vs WPA2 vs WEP vs Open)
  - PMF status
  - Channel plan quality (1/6/11 compliance, no adjacent channel interference)
  - Retry rate
  - Client signal strengths
  - Firmware age (from uptime)
  - SSID count
  - Roaming support (802.11k/r/v)
  - Bit rate configuration (legacy rates disabled)
- Weight each factor by impact
- Display as a letter grade: A (90+), B (75-89), C (60-74), D (45-59), F (<45)


